Response Rate by Primary HTC Characteristic

CCC identified the top hard-to-count characteristics for every census tract.

All Census Tracts

  • Looking at the top HTC characteristics in all census tracts, the most common top HTC characteristic is multi-unit structures, followed by foreign born population and crowded units.

  • In census tracts where the top HTC characteristic is lack of internet access, we see about 49.6% of households have responded so far. This is the current HTC group with the lowest response rate.

  • In census tracts where the top HTC characteristic is moved recently, we see that 66% of households have responded. This is the HTC group with the highest response rate.

What are Priority Communities by Demographics?

Priority communities are determined by calculating the combined self-response rate for census tracts that have higher than average population shares of various demographics (for example, higher than average share of limited English proficient speakers). Census tracts where more than half of the population lives in group quarters have been excluded.

Priority communities for Foreign Born & LEP population
Central-Alameda
Downtown
Historic South-Central
Pico-Union
University Park

Priority communities for targeting outreach to limited English proficient speakers & people born outside of the US are located in Central and South LA.

These communities have low self-response rates in tracts where the share of LEP and foreign born populations are higher than average.

Priority communities by race/ethnicity

Many priority communities for targeting outreach to various demographic groups are located in South LA and Central LA, as these regions have the lowest overall self-response rates.

  1. Central-Alameda and Historic South-Central in South LA is a priority community for Black, Latinx and American Indian/Alaskan Native (AIAN) people living in low-responding tracts.

  2. Downtown LA is a priority community for Black, Asian and Native Hawaiian/Pacific Islander (NHPI) populations living in low-responding tracts.

  3. Pico-Union is a priority community for Asian, Latinx and American Indian/Alaskan Native (AIAN) people living in low-responding tracts.

Priority Communities by Region

  • We have identified priority communities in each region across the country. In regions with more HTC communities we have identified up to 5 communities per region.

  • Priority communities were identified using four combined metrics: response rate, number of uncounted households, number of HTC tracts in the region, and the community mean HTC score.

  • In each community we have identified the top HTC characteristic.
